### Shadow DOM Styling Isolation

Shadow DOM creates style encapsulation—external styles don't pierce the shadow boundary by default. Use ::part to expose internal elements for styling, and ::slotted to style light DOM children within slots. CSS custom properties can cross the boundary.

```typescript
/* Component internal styles (shadow DOM) */
::part(button) { background: blue; }

/* Host/light DOM styling it */
my-component::part(button) { background: green; }

/* Style slotted content */
::slotted(h2) { color: red; }

/* Custom properties cross the boundary */
:host { --primary-color: blue; }
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking all shadow DOM can be styled externally—you must explicitly export parts; CSS properties don't inherit into shadow DOM by default (only custom properties do).

