### CSS-in-JS vs Traditional CSS Trade-offs

CSS-in-JS provides component scoping, dynamic styling, and critical CSS extraction but adds runtime overhead and larger bundles. Traditional CSS is faster initially but requires careful naming conventions and manual tree-shaking. Choose CSS-in-JS for design systems; use CSS modules for performance-critical apps.

```typescript
/* CSS-in-JS: Dynamic styling, scope isolation */
const Button = styled.button`
  background: ${props => props.primary ? 'blue' : 'gray'};
`;

/* Traditional CSS: Zero runtime overhead */
/* button.module.css */
.button { background: gray; }
.button.primary { background: blue; }

/* Trade-off: Bundle size vs runtime performance */
```

**Common interview trap:** CSS-in-JS is always faster—it adds 10-30KB overhead and runtime parsing; traditional CSS modules with static extraction often outperform for non-interactive styles.

